<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-527-050  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 527 050.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  July 1990 v8 n7 p70(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T pushes office software. (Rhapsody work-flow automation toolset)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Furger, Roberta.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>ATandamp;T plans to introduce Rhapsody, a new office environmentdesigned for 'work flow automation,' in the fall of 1990.andO;Rhapsody is a network-based application suite that uses aclient/server architecture based on HP's object-oriented NewWaveenvironment.andP;  It will work under OS/2, Microsoft Windows, and UNIXand includes a back-end server portion based on the ATandamp;Timplementation of Microsoft LAN Manager for Windows.andP;  Work-flowautomation will let users track processes across departments andcompany locations and automate virtually all activities.andP;  A'Meeting Manager' feature schedules facilities and sends agendasand minutes to attendees via electronic mail.andP;  Analysts warn thatATandamp;T may have difficulty selling Rhapsody because customers areconservative when buying office automation systems and because thenew technology would cause major changes in work styles.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Work Group ComputingOffice AutomationClient/Server ArchitectureGraphical User InterfaceOperating EnvironmentsProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   ATandamp;T: slow sell in offices. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>